<subSubSection id="C3116551D65BC77240CCF993FD154F88" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BB436DAD65BC77240CCF993FD154F88" blockId="2.[151,775,1292,1925]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis id="B97FEAC8D65BC77240CCF993FEC24F08" box="[173,286,1549,1573]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Etymology</emphasis>
. Generic name is a combination of the black appearance of the specimen (Greek μελάνω) and the generic name 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B4D59D65BC7724153F9D0FE624F48" box="[306,446,1614,1637]" class="Insecta" family="Ripiphoridae" genus="Macrosiagon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97FEAC8D65BC7724153F9D0FE624F48" box="[306,446,1614,1637]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Macrosiagon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
[
<bibRefCitation id="EF9A4B2BD65BC77241ACF9D3FE3B4F48" author="Hentz NM" box="[461,487,1613,1637]" journalOrPublisher="Trans Am Phil Soc. Philadelphia (NS)." pageId="2" pageNumber="3" pagination="458 - 463" part="3" refId="ref9839" refString="28. Hentz NM. Remarks on the use of the maxillae in coleopterous insects, with an account of two species of the family Telephoridae, and of three of the family Mordellidae, which ought to be the type of two distinct genera. Trans Am Phil Soc. Philadelphia (NS). 1830; 3, 458 - 463, pl. XV." title="Remarks on the use of the maxillae in coleopterous insects, with an account of two species of the family Telephoridae, and of three of the family Mordellidae, which ought to be the type of two distinct genera" type="journal article" year="1830">28</bibRefCitation>
]. Feminine in gender. Te name is registeredunder ZooBank LSID urn:lsid:zoobank. org:act:46B9D135-5214-4999-9F2B-0BF4133F5F7F.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3116551D65BC77240CCF930FB8C48A8" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BB436DAD65BC77240CCF930FB8C48A8" blockId="2.[151,775,1292,1925]" lastBlockId="2.[813,1437,237,1893]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis id="B97FEAC8D65BC77240CCF930FEC14FE8" box="[173,285,1710,1733]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Tis genus is characterized by having a long and slender body, long elytra, acute, convex and partially dehiscent, small head, strongly flattened antero-posteriorly with vertex transversely planar, specialized mouthparts with elongated galea, bilobed ligula covered by bristles, prominent tibial spurs, tibial spur formula 2-2-2, antennae 11-segmented, mesonotal and metanotal legs with erect stiff spiniform setae, pretarsal claws serrate, abdominal segments laterally compressed, apical fields on hind wings with secondary “ghost” branches (sensu [
<bibRefCitation id="EF9A4B2BD65BC7724354FED3FC934848" author="Kukalova-Peck J &amp; Lawrence JF" box="[821,847,333,357]" journalOrPublisher="Can Entomol." pageId="2" pageNumber="3" pagination="181 - 258" part="125" refId="ref9774" refString="26. Kukalova-Peck J, Lawrence JF. Evolution of the hind wing in Coleoptera. Can Entomol. 1993; 125: 181 - 258." title="Evolution of the hind wing in Coleoptera" type="journal article" year="1993">26</bibRefCitation>
]: 186) and apices of hind wings asymmetrically overlapping in resting position.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
